PERCENTILES AND QUARTILES :

Percentile :

A percentile is a values below which a certain percentage of observations lie . Lets say we have an array that contains the following number :

A = [ 1 , 2 , 3 , 3 , 3 , 2 , 1 , 1 , 4 , 4 , 4 , 5 , 5 , 6 , 8 , 9 , 9 , 10 ]

Percentile of x = No of values below x / n * 100

Percentile of 9 = 15 / 18 * 100

                = 83 . 34 %

This means that 83 . 34 % of values in the array are less than 9 .


Quartiles :

25 percentile = 1st quartile
50 percentile = 2nd quartile
75 percentile = 3rd quartile


INTER QUARTILE RANGE :

This helps us know the rage from which a numerical category values can lie . This takes care of the outliers .

Lower fence = Q1 - 1.5 ( IQR )
Higher fence = Q3 + 1.5 ( IQR )

Q1 = ( 25 Percentile * ( n + 1 ) ) / 100
Q3 = ( 75 Percentile * ( n + 1 ) ) / 100

IQR = Q3 - Q1






CORRELATION AND COVARIANCE :

These both are statistical measures that are used to determine the relationship between 2 variables . Both are used to understand how changes
in 1 variable are associated with changes in the other variable .

COVARIANCE :

If the variables tend to increase and decrease together , the covariance is positive . If one tends to increase and the other tends to decrease
the covariance is negative

Covariance of an entire dataset = summation i=1 to n ( xi - xbar )( yi - ybar)/n-1

where xi and yi are the datapoints of a random variable x and ybar and xbar are sample mean .

Advantages :

quantify the relationship between x an y .

Disadvantages :

does not have a specific value range . can range from - infinity to + infinity .


CORRELATION :

It is also of 2 types :

1 ) PEARSON CORRELATION :

it ranges from -1 to 1 .

rho(x,y) = Covariance(x,y)  / ( sigma x * sigma y )

The more the value tends towards +1 the more +ve correlation bw x and y
The more the value tends towards -1 the more -ve correlation bw x and y


2 ) - SPEARMAN RANK CORRELATION

Pearson correlation is not able to capture the correlation between non linear data . To solve this we use Spearman rank correlation

Rs = cov(Rank of X , Rank of Y)/( sigma ( rank of X) * sigma ( rank of y ) )

Lets say we have a dataset

X   Y   R(x)    R(y)
1   2   2       1
3   4   3       2
5   6   4       3
7   8   5       5
0   7   1       4

This Correlation helps us in feature selection .




