                                            ANNOVA

ANNOVA or analysis of variance is a test used to compare the means of 2 or more groups . Two important components are :

1 ) - FACTORS ( DEPENDENT OR INDEPENDENT )
2 ) - LEVELS

EX : We have a medicine lets say paracetamol this becomes our factor and different dosages that is 125mg , 250mg , 500mg becomes the levels



ASSUMPTIONS IN ANNOVA:

1 ) - Normality of sampling distribution of mean - the dist. of sample mean is normally distributed .
2 ) - Absence of outliers
3 ) - Homogenity of Variance - Population variance in different levels of each independent variables are same
sigma1^2 = sigma2^2 = sigma3^2
4 ) - Samples are independent and random



TYPES OF ANNOVA :

1 ) - One way Annova : 1 factor with at-least 2 levels and these levels are independent

ex : doctor wants to test a new medication to decrease headache . They split participants into 3 groups [ 10mg , 20mg , 30mg ]

2 ) - Repeated Measure Annova : same as one way but the levels are dependent .

ex : a person is running 3 days simultaneously . Here the levels are the days and as the same person is running on 3 days the distance
may vary .

3 ) - Factorial Annova - 2 or more factors each  of which have at least 2 levels and this levels may either be dependent or independent .

ex : same ex as above but we include the factor of gender .



